01:27.477 --> 01:36.044
of the math instructors. His name was Shirley 
Lynch, who later went to A&M. And I got quite a bit

01:40.648 --> 01:48.595
interested in the geology, so I thought I'd then 
combine the electrical engineering and the

01:40.648 --> 01:48.595
geology. The only way I could think of combining it 
was as mining engineering. So I went to University

01:53.860 --> 01:56.742
of Illinois. on Lynch's recommendation. And, of 
course, I wasn't funded or anything. And so

02:04.927 --> 02:16.799
normally people who didn't have much money in 
those days would get a summer job to make enough

02:04.927 --> 02:16.799
money to pay tuition, books, and so forth, and get 
other jobs when they went there. Several of us had

02:16.819 --> 02:25.767
worked at the World's Fairs, say, in Chicago in 
1934 and in San Diego in 19... 35, mainly because

02:25.983 --> 02:32.872
World Fairs were places of new employment, and 
therefore they're a new job. So we earned enough

02:32.892 --> 02:40.281
money then to work to go to school the next year. So 
anyway, a couple of us worked in San Diego, then

02:40.922 --> 02:52.036
rode the freights and the trike and so forth to 
Urbana, Illinois. And the first job that's

02:52.056 --> 02:55.500
necessary is to get one that provides food, and 
waiting tables, and busing, and so forth. The next

03:01.597 --> 03:04.262
point is to get a job that provides money. And I had 
done drafting before, so I got a job with Francis

03:04.322 --> 03:13.138
Shepherd at that time, drafting, making maps. And 
then, of course, I took mining engineering

03:13.158 --> 03:19.530
courses and more geology. And it became evident 
after I'd been down a couple coal mines that

03:20.084 --> 03:28.655
geology was more interesting, straight geology. 
So I switched to straight geology for the

03:28.875 --> 03:33.682
bachelor's degree. And then about that time,

03:34.302 --> 03:41.832
Shepard and I started on a big map of California. 
And I spent the summer of 1936 in Washington. at the

03:47.489 --> 04:00.233
coast within the coast genetic survey making 
large-scale maps that later had to be reduced to a

03:47.489 --> 04:00.233
common scale and that increased the interest of 
course in oceanography and then shepherd had a

04:00.803 --> 04:09.593
$10,000 grant that provided for a year of ship time 
at Scripps and other things. And so alternate

04:10.353 --> 04:16.080
semesters, we'd go from University of Illinois to 
Scripps. And so then that provided—at that time,

04:16.100 --> 04:24.769
then I decided to go to oceanography all the way to 
marine geology. Those trips provided an

04:25.711 --> 04:36.707
opportunity for master's degrees and doctor's 
degrees for both Robert Dietz and me. So we were in

04:36.727 --> 04:43.697
the mainstream then of them.

